name: tungsten carbide powder production | tungsten carbide powder | Cutoff, U
description:
ecoQuery: https://ecoquery.ecoinvent.org/3.10/cutoff/dataset/22401/documentation

This dataset represents the production of 1 Kg tungsten carbide powder (WC-powder) by pyrometal-lurgy.  Production steps include calcination of ammonium paratungstate yielding tungsten blue oxide, the formation of tungsten metal powder through hydrogen reduction and the carburization of tung-sten metal powder to WC-powder. The carbon content in WC-powder is assuemd to be 6.1 %.;;The data for this dataset is taken from a LCI provided by Furberg et al. (2019) which was build based on data from literature.  ;Furberg, A., Arvidsson, R., Molander, S., 2019. Environmental life cycle assessment of cemented carbide (WC-Co) production. J. Clean. Prod. 209, 1126–1138. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jclepro.2018.10.272

The activity starts when the raw material enters the process

This activity ends with the production of 1 Kg WC-powder
category: C:Manufacturing/24:Manufacture of basic metals/242:Manufacture of basic precious and other non-ferrous metals/2420:Manufacture of basic precious and other non-ferrous metals

processDocumentation.timeDescription: Input for carbon black is based on a publication from 1979: Yih, S.W.H., Wang, C.T., 1979. Tungsten - Sources, Metallurgy, Properties and Applications.
processDocumentation.geographyDescription: This dataset represent tungsten carbide powder production outside of China
processDocumentation.technologyDescription: APT is calcined leading to the formation of tungsten blue oxide, H20 and NH3. For this inventory tungsten blue oxide is assumed to be pure WO3. NH3 gas is assumed to be recovered at a rate of 61 %. Tungsten blue oxide conversion to tungsten metal powder is conducted in a H2 reducing atmos-phere. Finally, tungsten metal powder is mixed with carbon black and carburized in a reducing H2 at-mosphere. CO2 formation result from the burning of excess CH4 and C2H2 formed during carburiza-tion. Total fugitive loss of H2 was calculated to be 6.7 % based on the inventory provided by Furberg et al. (2019) and excess H2 was assumed to be recovered completely.;Furberg, A., Arvidsson, R., Molander, S., 2019. Environmental life cycle assessment of cemented carbide (WC-Co) production. J. Clean. Prod. 209, 1126–1138. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jclepro.2018.10.272
